<p>individuals affected by noma live in the sub-Saharan countries of Chad, Ethiopia, Mali, 
Mauritania, Niger, Nigeria, Senegal and Sudan.71 Cases are reported from other countries in 
Africa, Asia and Latin America,72 as figure 1 shows. A medical paper on noma in the Lao 
People&#8223;s Democratic Republic concludes that &#8220;it is likely that it is much more frequent in 
remote Asian rural communities than is currently appreciated&#8221;.73 
</p>
<p>Figure 1 
<b>Global distribution of noma
</b></p>
<p>74 
</p>
<p> 
35. According to estimates released by WHO in 1998, 140,000 individuals contract 
noma on a yearly basis;75 100,000 of these are children.76 The survival rate is between 10 
and 20 per cent, which means that at least 110,000 people, the vast majority of which are 
children, die every year because of noma.77 According to the WHO <i>World Health Report 
1998</i>, 770,000 persons survived the disease with heavy sequelae.78 
</p>
<p>36. In 2003 data on the incidence of noma have been calculated based on information 
from patients which have been admitted with the disease in two hospitals in Sokoto, 
Nigeria.79 By extrapolating the incidence from north-western Nigeria to the countries 
bordering the Sahara Desert, the research showed an annual incidence of 25,600 cases for 
</p>
